" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 271 "3.  Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.
  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra asserts that every non-constant p
olynomial (with complex-valued coefficients) has a root (a zero, a sol
ution).  A consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra is that e
very polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 276 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has exactl
y " }{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 108 " roots.  An alternate formulation \+
of this consequence would be that every non-constant polynomial of deg
ree " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 38 " can be factored into a product o
f a  " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the followi
ng polynomials:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "I.    " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "f := x^3-x^2-2*x" "6#>%\"fG,(
