-1 380 "A related theorem about finding roots of polynomials (equivale
ntly factoring polynomials into a product of linear factors) asserts t
hat if the polynomial has real coefficients -- all of the polynomials \+
we have considered (and will consider) have had real coefficients -- t
hen any complex roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For
 example, both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT 
-1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in c
onjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new polyno
mials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show \+
that the any complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs
." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
